07039nam a22008055i 9781553395409DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815533954097 a10.1515/97815533954092doi  a(DE-B1597)657795  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN107b.F34 2018eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a361.6/1097122300aFederalism and the Welfare State in a Multicultural World /ced. by Elizabeth Goodyear-Grant, John Myles, Will Kymlicka, Richard Johnston. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b28 figures, 17 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQueen's Policy Studies Series ;v19800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tBiographies -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: The Progressive’s Dilemma -- tThe Multiple Pathways to Social Policy: Complex Diversity and Redistribution in Canada -- tFederalism and the Welfare State -- tIs Canadian Federalism Market-Preserving? The View from the Bond Markets -- tQuebec’s New Politics of Redistribution Meets Austerity -- tDesigning a Basic Income Guarantee for Canada -- tFederalism, Race, and the American Welfare State -- tPolitical Institutions and the Welfare State in Canada and the United States -- tFederalism, Immigration, and Diversity -- tCanada’s Changing Citizenship Regime Through the Lens of Immigration and Integration -- tThree Hypotheses on the Relevance of Federalism for the Politics of Immigration and Welfare -- tIs There a Tradeoff Between Ethnic Diversity and Redistribution? The Case of Income Assistance in Canada -- tDiversity and Solidarity -- tMulticulturalism Policy and Support for the Welfare State -- tDoes Everyone Cheer? The Politics of Immigration and Multiculturalism in a Canada -- tThe Life and Death of Multiculturalism -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil the 1990s social policy played an integrative role in Canada, providing a counter-narrative to claims that federalism and diversity undermine the potential of social policy. Today, however, the Canadian model is under strain, reflecting changes in both the welfare state and the immigration-citizenship-multiculturalism regime. Federalism and the Welfare State in a Multicultural World illustrates that there are clear trends that, if unchecked, may exacerbate rather than overcome important social cleavages. The editors argue that we are at a crucial moment to re-evaluate the role of social policy in a federal state and a multicultural society, and if federalism and diversity challenge traditional models of the nation-building function of social policy, they also open up new pathways for social policy to overcome social divisions. Complacency about, or naive celebration of, the Canadian model is unwarranted, but it is premature to conclude that the model is irredeemably broken, or that all the developments are centrifugal rather than centripetal. Social policy is integral to mitigating divisions of class, region, language, race, and ethnicity, and its underlying values of solidarity and risk-sharing also make it a critical mechanism for nation-building. Whether social policy actually accomplishes these goals is variable and contested. The essays in this volume provide some timely answers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 0aMulticulturalismzCanada. 0aWelfare statezCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBanting, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesco, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloemraad, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat